<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-start') %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Literati painting (文人畫) refers to the tradition of scholar-amateurs who painted as an extension of poetry, calligraphy, and self-cultivation rather than as professional craftsmen. Favoring ink over color, spontaneity over finish, and expression over literal description, literati artists — from the Song through the Ming and Qing — made painting a vehicle for character and philosophical reflection, with subjects such as the Four Gentlemen and reclusive landscapes carrying deep moral and personal meaning.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-end') %>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
